- Speaker A tells the interviewee that he puts everything off until the last minute and pays the price for it. He doesn't learn from it and keeps doing it. The interviewer thinks it might be some sort of self punishment or something.
- The two things that bother the most are the things that keep cropping up day by day. One is that there is no inner drive to do something and the other is that it is hard to make decisions.
- Speaker A started reading more critically this week. This was encouraging because it was a step away from mental laziness.
- Neil and the others are talking about their dissatisfaction with the progress of their writing. Neil thinks it is hard to start from scratch when he is in the middle of a maelstrom.
- Speaker A and Speaker B talk about movies. Speaker B thinks movies have a compelling pull and Speaker A always thinks of things in the long run. Speaker C thinks movies are a real addiction.
- Speaker A tells the group about the thought process of going round and round in a circle in his senior year in high school. He doesn't like it because he doesn't get any clear perspective.
- Speaker C wants to know what it is in me that is working against him.
- Speaker C thinks the demands on people to meet deadlines and so on are kind of fortunate because it saves them from facing the complete frustration they would feel if nobody forced them to do anything.
- Speaker C thinks the second interview was a very interesting one and shows the way in which therapy begins to get underway. The client has begun on the process of self exploration and he will slowly follow that inward need to explore the areas that cause tension.
